Approach

Since each row is sorted and the first element of every row is greater than the last element of the previous row, we can think of the entire matrix as a single sorted 1D array.

Instead of searching row by row, I perform a binary search. For any index mid, I can convert it back to its corresponding row and column using:


row = mid / n
col = mid % n


This way, I can treat the matrix like one large sorted array without actually creating a new array. For each middle position found during binary search, I convert it back to its corresponding row and column and check the value. If the value matches the target, I return `true`. If the value is smaller than the target, I know the target can only be on the right side, so I move my search there. Otherwise, I search the left side. I keep narrowing down the search space until I either find the target or exhaust all possibilities.

This gives a logarithmic search time over all elements in the matrix.

---

### Solution

class Solution {
public:
    bool searchMatrix(vector<vector<int>>& matrix, int target) {

        int rows = matrix.size();
        int cols = matrix[0].size();

        int left = 0;
        int right = rows * cols - 1;

        while (left <= right) {

            int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;

            int row = mid / cols;
            int col = mid % cols;

            int value = matrix[row][col];

            if (value == target) {
                return true;
            }
            else if (value < target) {
                left = mid + 1;
            }
            else {
                right = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
};


### Complexity

Time Complexity: O(log(m * n))
Binary search is performed over all m * n elements, and the search space is cut in half during each iteration.

Space Complexity: O(1)
Only a few variables are used, regardless of the size of the matrix.
